I've never had a thing to do with H.F. machines but as a general rule
setting machine tools involves mounting them on some surface that is
completely stationary. Once the machine is mounted it is "leveled",
i.e. adjusted by shimming, or otherwise moving the mounting feet,
until the ways are parallel over their entire length. This is usually
checked by use of a precision level, thus the term "leveled".

Ensuring that the ways, the surfaces that the various parts of the
machine move on, are parallel and/or at right angles ensures that the
machine will be as accurate as possible, always considering the in
built accuracy of the machine itself.

