All of the larger machine tools at work are on custom poured concrete
foundations. Some, such as the low speed balancing machine (600rpm with a 50
ton rotor) have raised bases that were made in the way that you suggest...
only more so!

I would suggest that if you think you will be moving it in the next decade or
so, to paint a good coat of gloss paint on most of the floor where it is going
to go. The concrete won't bond to the painted bit and should allow it to break
away when you apply the sledge hammer to it.

Make a jig (or use the base of the mill) to hold threaded tubes for the mill's
mounting bolts, they can then be cast directly into the obelisk without having
to drill holes later.

The only think I can see wrong with the idea is that you loose out on
potential cupboard space in the stand. You could always cast a couple of steel
boxes into the stand to act as cupboards, and lessen the amount of concrete
though!

Mark Rand
